#Text=It evolves around fatigue testing of mesoscale specimens to increase damage detection sensitivity, data fusion through multimodal registration to address data heterogeneity, and image-based data-driven damage localization.
#Text=Resulting data sets capture the interaction of damage with microstructural features and hold the potential to unravel a mechanistic understanding.

#Text=This includes techniques such as the near-field and far-field High Energy X-ray Diffraction Microscopy (HEDM) as well as diffraction contrast tomography (DCT), which arguably can address these demands to the largest extent.
#Text=Exemplarily, the material EN 1.4003 (AISI 3Cr12), a ferritic stainless steel, is considered in this work.
#Text=In Table 1 the average values of the alloying elements are summarized.
#Text=Planar, mesoscale fatigue specimens were produced from as-received rod material with a diameter of 21 mm, which previously underwent hot rolling, grinding, cold drawing, and annealing.
#Text=The specimen's fabrication employed different processing steps, including electrical discharge machining to fabricate disks and laser cutting to define the specimen shape, shown in [16].
#Text=As opposed to the there described geometry, a thickness of 340 m and minimal (center) beam width of 480 m were targeted.

#Text=The electropolishing process introduces a slight, beneficial specimen edge rounding circumventing crack initiation at otherwise sharp edges, facilitating inference of microstructure-related influence factors.
#Text=As indicated in Fig. 1, different characterization steps were performed on the SEM, encompassing Everhart-Thorley secondary electron (SE2) (3) and EBSD data (4) acquisition.
#Text=These measurements utilized a Zeiss Supra 40VP equipped with an EDAX TSL EBSD system.
#Text=For EBSD data, the working distance (WD), scan step size, and aperture were chosen to be 18 mm, 0.6 μ m and 60 mm, respectively.
#Text=Activating high current mode enabled high electron collection rates.
#Text=Dynamic focusing ensured good pattern quality across the whole region of interest.
#Text=As a part of the automated postprocessing routine, EBSD pixels that exhibit confidence index (CI) below 0.05 are discarded, and the grains and grain boundary segments are reconstructed.
#Text=Pixel misorientations between adjacent EBSD pixels exceeding 5°were considered to separate grains.
#Text=Grains consisting of less than eight indexed pixels are discarded.
#Text=The EBSD data reveals an average equivalent grain diameter of about 30 μ m and single grains up to 100 μ m diameter.

#Text=Therefore, a Veeco$^{®}$ Dimension V AFM was utilized to conduct scans after fatigue in regions of protrusions at the specimen surface.
#Text=A segmentation methodology was devised to detect damage locations pixel-wise in the high-resolved post-mortem SEM stitched images to assist the in-situ light optical imaging.
#Text=To characterize the in-situ imaging, the dependence of its resulting local grayscale image texture on the slip trace topography (i.e., extrusions, intrusions, protrusions) is investigated.
#Text=Therefore, atomic force microscopy (AFM) maps are acquired.
#Text=Typical instances of microstructurally short cracks and protrusions developing the highly chromium-alloyed, ferritic EN 1.4003 steel are depicted in Fig. 7.
#Text=In contrast to the literature, where most damage in the HCF/VHCF regime is reported to be associated with (internal) pore or
#Text=inclusion defects [41], for the material and loading conditions at hand (low amplitude bending), damage emerged at and is localized to grain boundaries at the surface predominantly.
